          "field_name": "eligibility_text",
          "candidate_value": "A high-ratio mortgage requires a down payment of less than 20% of the property\u2019s value, while a conventional mortgage requires a down payment of 20% or more.",
          "evidence_chunk_id": "chunk-d019163ad7781df0",
          "evidence_text_excerpt": "High-ratio vs. conventional mortgages\nWhen you buy a new home, you need at least 5% of the property\u2019s value for the down payment. Any extra money you put down is up to you. The type of mortgage you qualify for is based on the amount of your down payment:\nA high-ratio mortgage means your down payment is less than 20% of the property\u2019s value. With a high-ratio mortgage, you will have to buy mortgage insurance from the Canada Mortgage Housing Corporation (CMHC), Canada Guaranty or Sagen TM to protect the lender against loss if you fail to make your mortgage payments.\nA high-ratio mortgage means\nA conventional mortgage means your down payment is 20% or more of the property\u2019s value. With a conventional mortgage, you don\u2019t need to buy mortgage insurance.\nA conventional mortgage means\nYour choice of high-ratio or conventional will depend on how much money you have for a down payment.",
